        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="4">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Allow the engine to cool down before removing the pressure cap. ALWAYS INSULATE the cap by
                        wrapping it with a thick, heavy cloth. To prevent possible injury from scalding water or steam,
                        DO NOT pull the pressure cap off immediately when it has been loosened to the first "notch."
                        Pause momentarily to allow time for excess pressure to release through the overflow tube.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove grill.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Close the heater feed and return valves.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drain the engine coolant in a clean container for reuse if desired.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove hoses from fill tube assembly.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove three bolts that attach the old style fill tube to the radiator support. Remove
                    the fill tube assembly.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a Sawsall or equivalent to trim the passenger side radiator support flush with the
                    radiator mounting flange. Use a die grinder or equivalent to remove all sharp edges (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412131">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9412131" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9412131.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mount the new fill tube assembly using the top front radiator mounting hole and the
                    corresponding hole on the rear of the bracket. Tighten mounting bolts to 34-38 ft.lbs (46-51 N&#8226;m)
                    (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412132">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9412132" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9412132.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">From inside the engine compartment, use the fill tube bracket as a template to drill a
                    &#x215C; inch diameter hole through the fan shroud to gain access to the weld nut on the radiator
                    support member (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412132">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Use care when drilling not to damage the threads in the weld nut.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a &#x215C;"-16 &#215; 1" bolt into the hole and tighten to 34-38 ft.lbs (46-51 N&#8226;m).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install hose part number 2643493R1, 54 inches long with protective conduit part number
                    2643669R1, 44 inches long between the fill tube and the elbow at the engine water inlet (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412133">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9412133" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9412133.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reconnect the remaining radiator hose to the second fill tube outlet (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412133">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>Insure smooth operation and no hose rubbing, especially in the stored position.</para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install hose part number 2643544R1, 114 inches long between the top fill tube outlet and
                    the coolant recovery container (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9412134">Figure 4</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9412134" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9412134.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The elbow outlet on the fill tube is supplied plugged and is not used for this
                            procedure.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fill the radiator. Refer to CTS-5071R, Engine Cooling System, in the CTS-5000 Master
                    Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Open the heater feed and return valves.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start the vehicle and purge all air out of the cooling system. Add coolant as
                    required.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check SCA concentration. Use a DCA4 test kit to test the DCA4 additive level, and a
                    Nalcool test kit to test the Nalcool coolant additive level. Refer to TSI-94-12-01 for more
                    information on Supplemental Coolant Additives (SCA'S).
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
